(1) Two different medical technologies are being considered. The first requires more labor input but would require only \$20 million per year to finance the equipment used; the annual cost to produce $x$ grams of output has been estimated to be $20 + 12x^{2/3}$. The second technology is more automated but requires \\$50 million per year to finance; its annual cost has been estimated to be $50 + 8x^{1/2}$. Determine the grams per year at which both technologies would have the same cost.

In [1]:
using Optim, Plots
f(x) = 20 + 12x^(2/3)
g(x) = 50 + 8x^(1/2)
plot(f, 0, 20, label="Manual")
plot!(g, 0, 20, label="Automated")
x = optimize(x -> abs(f(x) - g(x)), 0, 20).minimizer
str = "\\nSame Cost at " * string(round(x, digits=2)) * " Grams per Year\\n"
scatter!([x], [f(x)], label="Same Cost", title=str)

(2) Forty potential sites for tracking devices have been identified throughout a wildlife preserve. Dedicated fiber-optic cables will be installed in a straight line from each tracking device to a station that can receive input from up to five devices.

(2a) Determine the location for the station, and at which sites tracking devices should be installed so that the total length of cable is minimized. The coordinates of the potential sites can be generated by running the following code:

using Random
Random.seed!(93645)
P = 1000*rand(40,2)
In [2]:
using Random, Optim, Plots
Random.seed!(93645)
P = 1000*rand(40,2)
dist2(x,P) = sqrt.(sum((x' .- P).^2, dims = 2))
function dist2min5pts(x, P)
    d = dist2(x, P)
    idx = sortperm(d[:])
    return d[idx[1:5]]
end

TD = Inf
i, x = NaN, NaN
for i = 1:size(P,1)    # Use each point in P as starting point and keep best found
    x = optimize(x -> sum(dist2min5pts(x, P)), P[i,:]).minimizer
    TD = sum(dist2min5pts(x, P))
    println(i,": ",TD)
    if TD < TD
        i,x,TD = i,x,TD
    end
end

xrng = -10:1010
yrng = -10:1010
contour(xrng, yrng, (x1,x2) -> sum(dist2min5pts([x1, x2],P)))
scatter!(P[:,1], P[:,2], label="Sites", 
    series_annotations = text.([string(i)*"  " for i in 1:size(P,1)], :right, 7))
scatter!([x[1]], [x[2]], label="Receiving Station")

(2b) Describe (in words, no code) a possible procedure to install tracking devices at each site if seven additional identical receiving stations were to become available.

Your Procedure: Locate the first station and install it is five tracking devices, then remove those five sites and determine where a second station should be located and then removing its five sites, repeating for the remaining six stations. This type of greedy procedure is not likely to be optimal, but it is simple to implement and likely to be very close to the optimal location allocation solution.

using DataFrames, CSV, Plots, Random, Statistics, Optim
df = DataFrame(CSV.File("NL_Opt-3-Data.csv"))
d,o = Int.(df.Demand),Int.(df.Orders)
display(plot(d, legend=false, xlabel="Day", ylabel="Demand", title="Original Demand"))
display(plot(d[randperm(length(d))], legend=false, 
        xlabel="Day", ylabel="Demand", title="Permuted Demand"))
display(plot(d[randperm(length(d))], legend=false, 
        xlabel="Day", ylabel="Demand", title="Permuted Demand"))

p = 5                                    # Unit price
c = 1                                    # Unit cost
f(q,di) = p*min(q,di) - c*q             # Profit (f  f\pi<TAB>)  
f(q,d) = sum([f(q,di) for di in d])    # Total profit (f  f\Pi<TAB>)

 = f(216,d)
df = DataFrame(Procedure = "Baseline", Total_Profit = Int(round()))

 = f(mean(d),d)
push!(df,("Single parameter mean", Int(round())))

 = f(median(d),d)
push!(df,("Single parameter median", Int(round())))

q = optimize(q -> -f(q,d), 0, 500).minimizer
 = f(q,d)
push!(df,("Single parameter max profit", Int(round())))

display(plot([o d], xlabel="Day", ylabel="Units", label=["Orders" "Demand"]))
scatter(o, d, xlabel="Orders", ylabel="Demand", label="(o, d)")
@show cor(o,d)
f(q,d) = sum([f(qi,di) for (qi,di) in zip(q,d)]);    # Total profit (using ZIP function)
 = f(o,d)
push!(df,("Using just order data", Int(round())))

fd(,o) = [1] .+ [2]o
 = optimize( -> -f(fd(,o),d), [0. 1.]).minimizer
 = f(fd(,o),d)
push!(df,("Linear regression", Int(round())))
plot!(o -> fd(,o),0,maximum(o), label="Linear")

fdQ(,o) = [1] .+ [2]o .+ [3]o.^2   # Quadratic model
Q = optimize( -> -f(fdQ(,o),d), [0. 1. 0.]).minimizer
 = f(fdQ(Q,o),d)
push!(df,("Quadratic regression", Int(round())))
display(plot!(o -> fdQ(Q,o),0,maximum(o), label="Quadratic", legend=:topleft))

 = (p - c)*sum(d)
push!(df,("Perfect prediction", Int(round())))

display(df)
